Path: Two years of Nushell
Content:




Stock cake photo with a 2
Happy birthday, Nushell!
Happy birthday, Nushell! Today marks the second year for Nushell since its first public release. We wanted to write a bit about what the last year has meant and share some of the highlights and lowlights along the way.
óŔ^archive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-08-23-two-years-of-nushell.mdŔ@5a0b1dc4fd2eeeac0356fe7b959f6ae87648cf6a7507efb92abc28b06fce7003Ľtitle: Two years of NushellĎ•FocusŕŠThrough out Nushell's first year, we had faith in the basics behind Nushell but couldn't guess how it would grow and what it might be able to do. As we progressed through this second year, the project gained a focus: 
to be the best tool for interactively working with your system and your data
.
It's a high bar to set, but we're happy to try to achieve that goal. To achieve it, we're focusing on three different parts of Nushell, each of which deeply connects to the other two.
íźźŕTitle: title: Two years of Nushell
Path: Focus
Content:
Through out Nushell's first year, we had faith in the basics behind Nushell but couldn't guess how it would grow and what it might be able to do. As we progressed through this second year, the project gained a focus: 
to be the best tool for interactively working with your system and your data
.
It's a high bar to set, but we're happy to try to achieve that goal. To achieve it, we're focusing on three different parts of Nushell, each of which deeply connects to the other two.
óŔ^archive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-08-23-two-years-of-nushell.mdŔ@d940d12b19402443001286d971b90ca1040e5d0f62dfe0c60d765c31dbc7662bĽtitle: Two years of NushellĎĶNushell, the languageŕ«Nushell (sometimes shortened to just Nu) is a language that allows you to easily create pipelines for working on structured data. As a language, Nushell has grown considerably over the last year. You're now able to make your own commands to process data, create aliases, variables, and much much more.
We've started collecting examples to share with each other as Nushell grows and our skill with it grows with it. You can check them out in the 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts] Nu Scripts repo
.
Dark theme vscode showing Nushell
To work with Nushell, we also published a 
[link: https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=TheNuProjectContributors.vscode-nushell-lang] vscode extension
.
íźźŕTitle: title: Two years of Nushell
Path: Nushell, the language
Content:
Nushell (sometimes shortened to just Nu) is a language that allows you to easily create pipelines for working on structured data. As a language, Nushell has grown considerably over the last year. You're now able to make your own commands to process data, create aliases, variables, and much much more.
We've started collecting examples to share with each other as Nushell grows and our skill with it grows with it. You can check them out in the 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts] Nu Scripts repo
.
Dark theme vscode showing Nushell
To work with Nushell, we also published a 
[link: https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=TheNuProjectContributors.vscode-nushell-lang] vscode extension
.
óŔ^archive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-08-23-two-years-of-nushell.mdŔ@07420ee1e125615a0bc60f9ec76d93da6f163f3d9b2e4092ec71a3e85de5ecdbĽtitle: Two years of NushellĎ≤Nushell, the shellŕFrom day #1, Nushell has always been intended to work well as a shell. It's even in the name ūüôā.
We've spent a lot of time this year steadily improving areas that make Nushell -- as a shell -- feel better, more stable, and generally easier to use. We've improved integrations with 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts/tree/main/virtual_environments] Python
, integrations with tools like 
[link: https://github.com/ajeetdsouza/zoxide] zoxide
 and 
[link: https://github.com/starship/starship] starship
, and more. That said, as more people have adopted it, we've learned more what regular shell users need. Lots of ideas going into next year as to places that Nushell can work better with the broader range of tools and techniques that commandline users use.
íźźŕGTitle: title: Two years of Nushell
Path: Nushell, the shell
Content:
From day #1, Nushell has always been intended to work well as a shell. It's even in the name ūüôā.
We've spent a lot of time this year steadily improving areas that make Nushell -- as a shell -- feel better, more stable, and generally easier to use. We've improved integrations with 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts/tree/main/virtual_environments] Python
, integrations with tools like 
[link: https://github.com/ajeetdsouza/zoxide] zoxide
 and 
[link: https://github.com/starship/starship] starship
, and more. That said, as more people have adopted it, we've learned more what regular shell users need. Lots of ideas going into next year as to places that Nushell can work better with the broader range of tools and techniques that commandline users use.
óŔ^archive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-08-23-two-years-of-nushell.mdŔ@fc19ee035ecc7c3f2547dbdccbcb17004a8e1f7021e59b362883d3636687c007Ľtitle: Two years of NushellĎŅNushell, the data analysis toolŕLA relatively new aspect of being an interactive tool for working with data is Nushell's recent adoption of supporting dataframes. Dataframes allow users to work with large datasets in an efficient way. Recent versions of Nushell, using dataframes, are able to process and aggregate data from 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.html#dataframes-elferherrera] 5 million line csv files in less than a second
. Did we mention dataframes are fast?
We'll be exploring how best to more-fully integrate dataframes with the rest of the Nushell features in the coming year.
íźźŕěTitle: title: Two years of Nushell
Path: Nushell, the data analysis tool
Content:
A relatively new aspect of being an interactive tool for working with data is Nushell's recent adoption of supporting dataframes. Dataframes allow users to work with large datasets in an efficient way. Recent versions of Nushell, using dataframes, are able to process and aggregate data from 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.html#dataframes-elferherrera] 5 million line csv files in less than a second
. Did we mention dataframes are fast?
We'll be exploring how best to more-fully integrate dataframes with the rest of the Nushell features in the coming year.
óŔ^archive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-08-23-two-years-of-nushell.mdŔ@948d3e282466e0c0125edb7cb370ba1c3de4d21708cffcfdbea1bd8dce88ace8Ľtitle: Two years of NushellĎŅSeeing what Nushell will becomeŕ¨With 0.32, we first 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/blog/2021-06-01-nushell_0_32.html#new-expression-syntax-sophiajt] got a glimpse of what the Nushell language will become
. With 0.34, we saw 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.html#dataframes-elferherrera] what data processing could be
. These recent releases help to sketch where Nushell will feel like when it hits 1.0.
One example that shows this off is the script we use every week to create the This Week in Nu newsletter. As you can see, 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts/blob/main/make_release/this_week_in_nu_release.nu] it's a full script
 of the sort you might write in Python or Ruby.
íźźŕĢTitle: title: Two years of Nushell
Path: Seeing what Nushell will become
Content:
With 0.32, we first 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/blog/2021-06-01-nushell_0_32.html#new-expression-syntax-sophiajt] got a glimpse of what the Nushell language will become
. With 0.34, we saw 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/blog/2021-07-13-nushell_0_34.html#dataframes-elferherrera] what data processing could be
. These recent releases help to sketch where Nushell will feel like when it hits 1.0.
One example that shows this off is the script we use every week to create the This Week in Nu newsletter. As you can see, 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts/blob/main/make_release/this_week_in_nu_release.nu] it's a full script
 of the sort you might write in Python or Ruby.
óŔ^archive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-08-23-two-years-of-nushell.mdŔ@1111cdc9cf0a65f066abb287460e34cd203b64e5b3b445daeb5c77ac2ede4495Ľtitle: Two years of NushellĎ¨Growing loveŕhWe're seeing a growing amount of love for Nushell as more people try it and share their experiences. Here are some tweets from the last few weeks:
Oh damn @nu_shell is awesome. It's a really powerful advancement over existing shells on unix!
The pandas style dataframe feature in nushell is Exploding head‚ô•
@nu_shell has fundamentally changed the way I interact with data on my computer. It's no longer a process to get anything out of a csv, etc. It's just... there. however I want it served up.
Acabo de probar el @nu_shell y estoy enamorao
Nu Shell is amazing. I can‚Äôt believe it took me this long to find it.
The Nushell repo has also felt a recent surge of interest. Since this time last year, the number of stars has nearly doubled!
image of with the number of GitHub stars doubling over the last year
Growing interest in Nushell (shown: number of GitHub stars)
íźźŕßTitle: title: Two years of Nushell
Path: Growing love
Content:
We're seeing a growing amount of love for Nushell as more people try it and share their experiences. Here are some tweets from the last few weeks:
Oh damn @nu_shell is awesome. It's a really powerful advancement over existing shells on unix!
The pandas style dataframe feature in nushell is Exploding head‚ô•
@nu_shell has fundamentally changed the way I interact with data on my computer. It's no longer a process to get anything out of a csv, etc. It's just... there. however I want it served up.
Acabo de probar el @nu_shell y estoy enamorao
Nu Shell is amazing. I can‚Äôt believe it took me this long to find it.
The Nushell repo has also felt a recent surge of interest. Since this time last year, the number of stars has nearly doubled!
image of with the number of GitHub stars doubling over the last year
Growing interest in Nushell (shown: number of GitHub stars)
óŔ^archive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2021-08-23-two-years-of-nushell.mdŔ@1023947a792c52d9ed40a3445f29e5616b04a29bbb85edb7d2c071d2e7163989Ľtitle: Two years of NushellĎŔ$Nushell getting used for real thingsŕűWe're getting feedback from folks using Nushell about how much time Nushell saves them everyday. One report mentioned that their daily processing of files was cut by as much as 30 minutes! Saving 30 mins per day is an enormous amount, and we're happy to help.
Another area where Nushell is getting used is to process 
[link: https://twitter.com/cocoronata] Covid data in Ecuador
 (you can see 
[link: https://github.com/cocoronata/ecuacovid-scripts] more recent scripts written all in Nushell here
).
íźźŕLTitle: title: Two years of Nushell
Path: Nushell getting used for real things
Content:
We're getting feedback from folks using Nushell about how much time Nushell saves them everyday. One report mentioned that their daily processing of files was cut by as much as 30 minutes! Saving 30 mins per day is an enormous amount, and we're happy to help.
Another area where Nushell is getting used is to process 
[link: https://twitter.com/cocoronata] Covid data in Ecuador
 (you can see 
[link: https://github.com/cocoronata/ecuacovid-scripts] more recent scripts written all in Nushell here
).
